author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
There has been a lot of discussion on Jevons Paradox for AI: does cheaper AI lead to more total usage?

The answer in this new paper seems to suggest that it doesn't happen in the short-run, but does in the long run. The short-run price elasticity ~1 (so no short-run paradox) but prices fell 1000x in two years & demand exploded. So Jevons happens over time, as firms gradually adopt more AI at lower prices in a very competitive and dynamic market.

Previous best was under 50%.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
A lot of discussion on open weights AI models seems to assume there is a clear incentive for building them. I don’t see how is the case. Unless you have no need for money (government sponsored?), there are no real ways to capture value from your investments in a model even as training cost increase over time.

Open weights AI just does not have the same economics as open source software. You can’t rely on volunteer effort to provide compute or do training runs and you will not be able to profit from inference on your model, sell related services or gain unique advantages from people building on your tool.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
An understudied, high-value issue in AI agents is how to have them write the best summaries of what they have done so far (think Claude's compress feature) since AI agents can't keep an entire project in their working memory.

These serve as what organizational theorists call "boundary objects" which preserve key meaning as a project progresses, and are the messages passed between different AI "selves" as they run out of context and need to start fresh.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
I did not expect that the PowerPoint killer would be something called Nano Banana Pro, but that is where its heading.

It makes the major efforts by all the other AI companies, including Microsoft, to crack PowerPoint by using python seem like a dead end.

The thing is that NotebookLM can just take source materials, a topic, directions, and an idea and make a very pretty, impactful deck. Hallucinations are very rare, though there are still some spelling and graphics issues. Editing capability is apparently coming and, despite the current hiccups, you can see exactly where this is going.

ImageGen is all you need?

(The slide deck is the result of me throwing my entire book into NotebookLM, by the way)

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
I meet a lot of very smart AI critics who never seriously try to make AI work for them by spending a couple of hours with a frontier model working on hard tasks. As a result they are often misinformed about the current state of AI.

People can be (and should be & are) critical after realizing what AI can do, but experience leads to better-informed and sharper critiques.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
There was a small flood of articles around GPT-5 talking about how AI development has plateaued (partially based on experiences with the GPT-5 router). Has there been any major articles with updates since it became clear that there was no such plateau?

I get that everyone has moved on the potential of a financial bubble as the next AI crisis (and maybe there is one, maybe not, but AI isn't vanishing either way), but it would help to have a retrospective about how the various (very real) barriers to AI, from model collapse to pre-training scaling, were overcome to keep the exponential development curve going for now.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
We tested one of the most common prompting techniques: giving the AI a persona to make it more accurate. 

It doesn't work. We found that telling the AI "you are a great physicist" doesn't make it significantly more accurate at answering physics questions, nor does "you are a lawyer" make it significantly worse.

This doesn't mean that personas can't be useful - for example, they change how the AI answers questions, the format of output, and maybe other factors as well. However, you aren't going to make the AI suddenly more accurate through role-play.

Link in comments.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
Summarizing 2025 in AI in a five bullets:
1) No sign of a slowdown in exponential pace of gains across many measures of ability
2) Jaggedness remains the main issue of AI
3) it is the early days for deployment, but many companies are now reporting positive ROI
4) GenAI became an industry, with industry-level impacts
5) AI is still weird

The longer version:
1) Predictions that AI "will hit a wall" have not yet come true, though the future always remains uncertain. However, lots of alternative approaches to continuing gains whether using LLMs or new architectures or hybrids are now being developed, and there is a lot of money to experiment with. I see a lot of confidence in continued gains from insiders.

2) The nature and shape of the jagged frontier have changed (math used to be a major weakness of LLMs) but the fact that AIs still underperform humans by a large amount in a variety of tasks creates bottlenecks in complex tasks that limit what work AIs can do. A growing frontier may alter that in the future.

3) AI went from a theoretically useful tool to one that companies are starting to see value from. But it is early. Actual transformation of processes and organizational structures has not yet begun, and any changes to the job market are unclear at this point.

4) As an industry, AI impacts are much larger scale than before, whether you consider that in terms of electrical use or economic impact (and risk) or political power. Viewing AI as a product alone obscures the fact that it is now a big business.

5) We have not resolved the core questions that make AIs weird: why a next-token prediction system is as good as it is, how to measure and interact with these systems, and what they may eventually become.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
I think this a hugely important point by an OpenAI researcher, but a few critical things:

1) AI is many things, not one thing. People may like using AI to get help for intimate things like writing a wedding speech or answering medical questions but be nervous about what it means for their job or society. One-dimensional surveys don't capture this.

2) When I talk to crowds about AI, I find that if you take objections seriously (and there are legitimate things to object to about AI, as well as some strawmen) then you can have a real conversation about how to use it in good ways while thinking about how to limit bad uses. People really do want to know how to use AI better to improve their lives, even folks who don't like AI, but have fears as well.

3) If you look at the history of major technological innovations, this sort of strong cultural divide happens often. It is also that AI is developing very quickly in ways that are confusing to many people. I have a lot of sympathy for the anxiety folks have as a result.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
It has been three years since ChatGPT launched

GenAI is the fastest adoption of an economically consequential technology in human history. And the speed & breadth of that adoption (as well as its continued exponential improvement) is why we have no handle on what it all means.

When a powerful general purpose technology is in the hands of a billion people, a lot of things are going to happen at once. A lot of things are already happening at once. There are few aspects of society - from education to work to the arts to how we communicate - that are not seeing early impact from AI. And likely much more change ahead.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
At this point, papers testing whether AI can or cannot do something should try to test the strongest case, as well as the default.

It is fine to say Llama 2 failed, but did a serious attempt to use GPT-5.1 Thinking in an agentic harness work? The null hypothesis is that AI fails to do something. The null is easy to not falsify - if you want AI to fail, it will fail through bad prompts or bad models or a failure to try to figure out what approaches might work for LLMs. Defending the null (ie saying “AI can’t do this”) thus requires “severe” tests in the Popper/Mayo sense: best attempts to make AI work to see if it can.

This approach helps reduce burden on future research - once something is proven to work for an LLM, it doesn’t need to be re-tested as often in the future. It also helps us better map the frontier.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
My first published academic paper was on Moore's Law and right now AI development looks similar: the steady exponential growth of Moore's Law was not the result of a single technology, but rather many different technologies over many decades that were ready to take over when one chip-making approach faltered. The regular pace of the Law served as a coordinating function so that an ever-changing group of competitors were pressured to create a self-fulfilling prophecy of continual capability growth.

Similarly, AI development has already hit a number of speedbumps that had to be overcome with new techniques and research (synthetic data approaches, reasoning, new uses for RL). But unless you are an insider (or follow AI closely on LinkedIn), you don't see those speedbumps: just steady exponential progress.

Given the amount of money and talent in the space, I expect that even if pre-training or whatever hits a wall, we will see a quick transition of the entire industry to one or more of the many other approaches people are developing. You can see this already: work on world models, alternatives to LLMs, new training methods, etc. Even alternative ecosystems that are betting on the rise of small, fine-tuned models, etc. Some of these techniques are coming from startups, others are being developed in the AI labs themselves.

People on social media tend to get into the little details, treating AI like a sport, cheering for or against teams and approaches. But over any reasonable span of time, it is possible that AI development looks like a smooth exponential on many metrics to everyone else.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
The main lesson of the past few weeks is that the major US AI labs all seem to have figured out a path forward in continuing the exponential pace of LLM improvement, at least for now. As a result, agents continue to advance in coding & in office tasks like PowerPoint, cost/performance improves, and hallucination rates continue to drop.

It also means we are still in an era where no model dominates everything. For people who do a lot of complex work with AI, you are going to be alternating between Gemini, Claude & ChatGPT. And that isn't only because models have specific skills, each has a personality that contributes to utility on tasks.

On the flip side, if you don't do a lot with AI, you can just pick one of the Big Three and run with it and you will be fine. They are all quite good!

data.text:

[Edit: I originally wrote that AI amplified creativity, which was a poor word choice, there were only some minor amplification effects. It preserved individual differences in creativity. I edited the post to reflect that change.]

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
Voice is one of the most useful ways to interact with AI to do work (talking is often faster and more natural than writing) but it seems to have been semi-abandoned for serious use outside of the “chat with a friend” case.

All of the voice modes only access older, quite weak models with low latency, making them zippy & fun but kind of useless.

If you don’t think of voice models as a fun chat, but rather as a way of working, it suggests that pauses are fine, even preferred (don’t talk with me unless you have something to say). And alternative UXs beyond “talk with your AI about the weather” become possible to explore.

Also I want to turn off the breathing, giggling, and disfluencies. Anthropomorphism can be helpful in many cases but it gets to be too much, especially for serious discussions. The tone is off and it feels ingratiating and slows things down.

author.headline: Associate Professor at The Wharton School. Author of Co-Intelligence

data.text:
Some of the most interesting challenges posed by AI are to organizational structures: how does AI alter the economies of scope that determine firm boundaries? How do they change transaction costs? Efficiency/creativity trade-offs?

We haven’t had to reorganize the underlying nature of firms since the U form (unitary CEO decision-maker with a functional structure) was replaced by the M form (distributed divisional decision-making) in the 1920s

Does this bring us back to centralized CEO decision-making? (I find the “AI as CEO” concept as expressed often lacks a basic understanding of why companies are organized the way that they are. People don’t really mean the AI as CEO, they mean that there is some new structural level below CEO where AI informs and coordinates production letting the C-level exert direct control)

Figuring this out will be the key to benefiting from AI.
